References.QuickCitation: Barron Ruben (1993) The effects of year-round education on achievement, attendance and teacher attendance in bilingual schools. , Northern Arizona University.
References.Title: The effects of year-round education on achievement, attendance and teacher attendance in bilingual schools
References.Abstract: This study was undertaken to determine the relationship between a single-track year-round school and a traditional calendar school regarding student achievement, student attendance, and teacher attendance in a bilingual community. A two-way multivariate analysis of variance (MANOVA) was used to assess the statistical significance of achievement data. The achievement areas were used as dependent variables. If a significant difference occurred, a two-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) was computed. If a significant difference across the years or a significant interaction were found, a Tukey a posteriori test was computed to reflect where the differences occurred. At Grade 5, students were tested in English using the CTBS. Traditional school students outperformed the year-round students in reading, language, and mathematics. At Grade 2, students were tested in Spanish using the SABE. Traditional school students showed a progressive drop in reading and mathematics while year-round students showed continued improvement. Student attendance data for tardies, unexcused absences, and excused absences were analyzed. The traditional students had decreasing tardies during the 4 years of the study, while tardies for the year-round students increased. The traditional students had significantly fewer unexcused absences than the year-round students and significantly more excused absences. Teachers from the two types of schools did not significantly differ in attendance rates and rates did not differ by the year in which the data were gathered. The conclusions from this study are: (1) The relationship between achievement and the type of school calendar depends, in part, on the language of instruction and on when the analysis is done. (2) Grade 5 students in the traditional calendar school achieved significantly higher than students in the year-round school. (3) Grade 2 students achieved significantly higher in the traditional calendar school during the first year of the study and significantly lower than year-round students during the third year. (4) Excused absences were significantly higher in the traditional school. (5) Unexcused absences were significantly higher in the year-round school. (6) Tardies were not influenced by the type of school calendar. (7) Teacher attendance was not influenced by the type of school calendar.

References.QuickCitation: Bechtel Ronald Eugene (1991) A study of academic growth in third-grade students and its relationship to year-round education. , Pepperdine University.
References.Title: A study of academic growth in third-grade students and its relationship to year-round education
References.Abstract: Statement of the problem. Year-round education in the South Bay Union School District was implemented to meet student population growth, with the potential of returning to a traditional calendar when those growth needs are met. The problem this study addresses is the possible impact of year-round education on academic achievement and whether there has been acceptable academic growth to continue year-round education programs. Procedures. The population of this study consisted of third grade students (N = 525), in eight elementary schools in the South Bay Union School District, that took the Comprehensive Test of Basic Skills, Form-U in May, 1989 and May, 1990. The researcher of this study collected data from the cumulative folders of analysis units from six multi-track year-round education (YRE) and two traditional calendar schools. Data were entered into a computer and were analyzed using Number Cruncher Statistical Systems (NCSS 4.2). Findings. The findings of this study were as follows: Using ANOVA, a significant difference (at 0.5) between pre and post tests was demonstrated by all eight schools within this study. Using four separate ANOVAs the four school types were examined pair-wise. With the exception of schools in their third year of YRE, homogeneity was evident within all school types (two years in YRE, one year in YRE, and traditional calendar). With respect to the ANOVA, three-year YRE are significantly different from two-year and one-year YRE but not traditional schools; and, traditional schools differ significantly from only one-year YRE schools. In examining the impact of potential covariates, it was found that the covariate, number of years a student was in attendance in YRE, was not significant. When that covariate was dropped from the analysis the only significant difference was still across the school types. ANOVA, ANCOVA, and Fishers' Least Significant Difference (LSD) statistical analyses found a consistent pattern throughout the observations. As a group, the YRE schools demonstrated greater mean score gains than the traditional schools. Both first and second year YRE schools displayed greater gains than the traditional calendar schools. Compared to third year YRE schools, the traditional calendar schools displayed a higher, although not significant difference in mean score gains.

References.QuickCitation: Bergin David A, Hudson Lynne M, Chryst Carolyn F, and Resetar Mark (1992) An afterschool intervention program for educationally disadvantaged young children. The Urban Review 24(3), 203-217
References.Title: An afterschool intervention program for educationally disadvantaged young children
References.Abstract: The research investigated the premise that if educationally disadvantaged children experience increased instructional time combined with an educational setting that is sensitive to their culture and that provides perceptions of control, enhanced achievement and interest in learning will result. The research setting was the Hilltop Emergent Literacy Project (HELP), an afterschool educational program serving poor, mostly African American five- to nine-year-olds (kindergarten to third grade) who reside in a subsidized apartment complex. A treatment group of 12 kindergartners was compared to a control group of 12 kindergartners. In the spring of kindergarten, the treatment group was outperforming the control group on standardized test scores, but both groups were below national norms. In the spring of first grade, the treatment group was still outperforming the control group and was above national norms in some areas. Report card data and qualitative indicators also provide evidence of the effectiveness of the program.

References.QuickCitation: Berninger V W, Abbott R D, Vermeulen K, and Fulton C M (2006) Paths to reading comprehension in at-risk second-grade readers. Journal of Learning Disabilities 39(4), 334-351 DOI: 10.1177/00222194060390040701
References.Title: Paths to reading comprehension in at-risk second-grade readers
References.Institution: Department of Educational Psychology, University of Washington, School Psychology Program, United States Department of Educational Psychology, University of Washington, Measurement, Statistics, and Research Design Program, United States Fairfax County Public School, VA, United States Box 353600, University of Washington, 322 Miller, Seattle, WA 98195-3600, United States
References.Abstract: Two studies of second graders at risk for reading disability, which were guided by levels of language and functional reading system theory, focused on reading comprehension in this population. In Study 1 (n = 96), confirmatory factor analysis of five comprehension measures loaded on one factor in both fall and spring of second grade. Phonological decoding predicted accuracy of real-word reading; automatic letter naming predicted rate of real-word reading; accuracy and rate of both real-word reading (more so than decoding of pseudowords) and text reading predicted reading comprehension; and Verbal IQ also predicted reading comprehension. In Study 2 (n = 98), the treatment group (before/after school clubs receiving an integrated instructional approach that was supplementary to the general reading program) improved significantly more in phonological decoding and state standards for reading fluency than the control group (general reading program that had some code instruction but emphasized commmprehension). The rate of phonological decoding explained 60.3% of real-word reading. Both treatment and control children improved significantly in reading comprehension, but controlling for pretreatment individual differences in oral vocabulary or in phonological decoding eliminated this effect. Taken together, the results of the two studies support two paths to reading comprehension: one from vocabulary and verbal reasoning, and one from written language that has multiple links between subskills: (a) alphabetic principle → phonological decoding, (b) automatic phonological decoding → accurate real-word reading, (c) automatic letter coding → automatic word reading, and (d) automatic word reading → fluent text reading. Instructional implications of both paths and the links within the written language are discussed.

References.QuickCitation: Berninger V W, Rutberg J E, Abbott R D, Garcia N, Anderson-Youngstrom M, Brooks A, and Fulton C (2006) Tier 1 and Tier 2 early intervention for handwriting and composing. Journal of School Psychology 44(1), 3-30 DOI: 10.1016/j.jsp.2005.12.003
References.Title: Tier 1 and Tier 2 early intervention for handwriting and composing
References.Institution: University of Washington, 322 Miller, Seattle, WA 98195-3600, United States
References.Abstract: Three studies evaluated Tier 1 early intervention for handwriting at a critical period for literacy development in first grade and one study evaluated Tier 2 early intervention in the critical period between third and fourth grades for composing on high stakes tests. The results contribute to knowledge of research-supported handwriting and composing instruction that informs practice as school psychologists are empowered to embrace the role of intervention specialist. The first study found that neurodevelopmental training (orthographic-free motor activities and motor-free orthographic activities) led to improved accuracy and legibility of letter formation, but that direct handwriting instruction with visual cues and verbal mediation led to improved automatic handwriting (rate of writing legible letters) and transfer to improved word reading. The second study found that neither motor training nor orthographic training alone added value to direct instruction in automatic letter writing and composing practice in developing handwriting skills, which transferred to improved word reading; but the added motor training did improve performance on a grapho-motor planning task for sequential finger movements that is relevant to composing. A related analysis showed that direct instruction with visual cues and memory delays may reduce reversals. A third study found that adding handwriting to reading instruction improved handwriting but did not add value to reading outcomes for at risk readers; reading instruction alone was beneficial for word reading, decoding, and comprehension. The fourth study showed that comprehensive, explicit instruction in the processes of composition led to more significant improvement, based on group and individual data, than did the regular fourth grade program, on high stakes writing assessment. © 2006 Society for the Study of School Psychology. Published by Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.

For the next 15 min they engaged in warm up activities (like athletes) that promote automatic letter writing and automatic phonemegrapheme correspondences in spelling. For the next 25 min, they did Writers Work (teacher-directed composing activities). For the last 10 min (before the 5 min allotted for clean-up), they did Word Play activities (such as word sorts, Bingo games with structure wordsprepositions, pronouns, conjunctions, and articlesthat cannot be completely spelled on the basis of phonemegrapheme correspondences, and search for MommyLongWordslong, morphologically complex words). (See Lesson Set 10, Berninger & Abbott, 2003)."
"During the first month, the Writers Work activities involved composing about teacher- provided prompts (phrases), with the goal of children becoming comfortable in getting their ideas down on paper; following the composing, children read their writing orally to each other in small groups and shared one thing they liked about each composition and one thing that the author might do to make it better. Then children completed a lesson on planning (with graphic organizers), a lesson on generating written text, and a lesson on reviewing and revising (also grade 4 benchmarks in the district) on each of four different topics for each of two genre-writing informational essays and writing persuasive essays. The goal for these lessons was to improve the quality of their writing in terms of discourse organization. Throughout the project, children revised their favorite compositions. Three times they chose their best writing for publication in a newspaper entitled bKids Writing for Kids,Q which was distributed to the general education classrooms in the same schools as the writing clubs. Authors used their pseudonyms unless they preferred to use their real name. Because the children had also been encouraged to illustrate their writing throughout the club sessions, some of these drawings were also selected for publication.[¬e]"

References.QuickCitation: Cason Cindy Barnes (1995) The impact of year-round school on student achievement, student/teacher attendance, and discipline. , The University of Alabama at Birmingham.
References.Title: The impact of year-round school on student achievement, student/teacher attendance, and discipline
References.Institution: The University of Alabama at Birmingham
References.Abstract: This study investigated whether year-round education positively impacts student achievement and other factors relative to student and teacher behaviors. The study utilized a descriptive research design and involved three schools in three Southeastern states. The research questions and null hypotheses were constructed to determine if any difference existed between students in reading and math achievement as measured by the Stanford Achievement Test. Other variables measured consisted of average number of days absent by students and teachers as well as average number of reported suspensions. Data regarding variables were gathered over a four-year period. This four-year period consisted of the two years prior to implementation of a year-round calendar and two years after implementation of a year-round calendar. Data from schools utilizing a 45-15 year-round education program were compared with data gathered from a match school within their district which had continued to operate a traditional calendar over the identical time period. A factorial analysis of variance (ANOVA) was utilized to determine if there was any difference between the groups. Results of the data analyses indicated a statistically significant difference in Stanford Achievement Test scores for reading for students involved in a 45-15 year-round education program. In a comparison of the means for all other variables an upward trend of the means in these year-round schools after implementation of the calendar indicated that year-round education could be a factor that positively influences math achievement, student/teacher attendance, and frequency of reported suspensions.

References.QuickCitation: Chase R A (2000) Hmong American partnership: 2HTN final report. St. Paul, MN: Wilder Research Center,
References.Title: Hmong American partnership: 2HTN final report
References.Abstract: In 1995, the Hmong American Partnership, a community-based organization in St. Paul, Minnesota, began a 5-year program, Hmong Youth Pride (Hluas Hmoob Tsim Nuj - 2HTN) to increase academic achievement, school commitment, cultural pride, parental effectiveness and ATOD awareness, family relationships, future aspirations and disapproval of ATOD use among a group of 211 Hmong youth age 9-12 years attending three Minneapolis and St. Paul elementary schools. The intervention used to achieve these goals included (1) small-group tutoring sessions twice a week after school led by Hmong program managers, (2) bi-weekly after school structured group activities, including Hmong language and cultural lessons, ATOD education and recreational activities, (3) activities involving parents of participating youth such as home visits, cultural gatherings, and parent training workshops, and (4) cultural in-service training in Hmong culture for staff and administrators of participating schools. The evaluation of the 2HTN primary prevention program was a quasi-experimental design with repeated measures at baseline, post-program, and one-year follow-up comparing program participants with comparison group cohorts that did not receive the intervention. Comparison groups were recruited as convenience samples. For the comparison groups, baseline and post-test measures were administered at the same time periods as the intervention group. Measures included academic achievement, attitudes towards school, cultural pride, ATOD attitudes, parental involvement at school, parenting skills, parental awareness of ATOD risks, tangible support in schools for Hmong, and parents feelings of support in school for Hmong. Over the five years, 211 students enrolled in 2HTN at the three program sites included in this evaluation; 52 of them (25%) stopped participating prior to completion. The program drop-outs were similar to participants on most demographic, academic and risk measures. Process research indicated that participants in the program had generally positive opinions about the content, implementation and impact of the program, though all groups had some criticisms and suggestions for change, including the need for better coordination and communication between program staff and teachers, more consistent discipline for students but a more flexible and evolving curriculum to encourage sustained interest, greater parent involvement in the program and better staff/parent communication. Outcomes analysis demonstrates that students participating in 2HTN often showed large improvements in age-adjusted academic performance and these improvements were significantly greater than those seen among comparison youth who do not receive treatment. The intervention also had a demonstrable impact on parental reports of involvement in school activities, and parental concern about how their children were treated as Hmong. Less clear-cut were results with regard to youth's school attitudes and cultural pride: some cohorts showed significant positive change relative to their comparison group, but not all. Results with regard to future and family risk, youth andparent ATOD attitudes, and effective parenting were weaker and inconsistent over time.

References.QuickCitation: Chen Zengshu (1994) Year-round education: High school student achievement and teacher/administrator attitudes. , United States International University.
References.Title: Year-round education: High school student achievement and teacher/administrator attitudes
References.Abstract: The problem. The purpose of the study was to evaluate the outcome of American year-round high school programs by comparing students' achievement in traditional and year-round high schools and by determining teachers' and administrators' opinions of the advantages and disadvantages of a year-round high school program. Method. The study compared students' achievement in a traditional high school (control group) and a single track year-round high school (experimental group), and surveyed the opinions of teachers and administrators at three multi-track year-round high schools regarding the advantages and disadvantages of the multi-track year-round high school program. Results. A comparison of students' achievement showed that on the CTBS mean scores, the experimental group was significantly higher than the control group (p $<$.05); on the Scholastic Aptitude and the CAP tests mean scores, no statistically significant differences were found. In percentage of growth, the experimental group was higher than the control group; on the Stanford Achievement Test, the experimental group's mean score was significantly lower than the control group's at the first year; however, by the third year, its mean score was higher than the control group's in percentage increasing. Moreover, the experimental group mean scores and percentage of increase on CTBS and CAP were higher after the year-round program was introduced than before. A survey of teachers/administrators at three multi-track year-round high schools revealed that more than half of the respondents believed the advantages of year-round education outweighed the disadvantages. Advantages cited were: increases student enrollment; allows students to remediate immediately by repeating a class or switching to a more appropriate course during intersession; provides students with year-round opportunity for enrichment/remediation, athletic programs, and employment; allows families to take vacations at various times. Disadvantages cited were: disrupts family vacation plans, and causes difficulties when students transfer between year-round and traditional schools. Seventy-five percent of the respondents with five or more years of year-round education experience preferred a year-round program, while 25 percent preferred a traditional schedule.

References.QuickCitation: Consolie Pamela Gilbert (1999) Achievement, attendance, and discipline in a year round elementary school. , University of Georgia.
References.Title: Achievement, attendance, and discipline in a year round elementary school
References.Abstract: The purpose of this study was to explore the impact of year round schools (YRS). Schools using an alternative calendar format, as opposed to a traditional, nine month, September to June calendar have been used sporadically in this country for about 100 years. During this time, limited research has been conducted to quantify the effects of the approach on student achievement, attendance, and behavior. Fifth grade students from a school in Georgia using a year round school calendar were compared to fifth grade students from another elementary school, within the same district, using a traditional calendar approach. The schools were matched in terms of socio-economic status and minority rates. Data were gathered and compared for both groups regarding attendance, achievement in math and reading, and out of school suspensions. Further, a cohort comparison for those individuals attending school under the year round approach during both their third and fifth grade years was conducted to determine if improvements, in terms of achievement, were experienced. Correlations were conducted to determine if their was a significant relationship among attendance and achievement for students attending school under a year round approach. Statistical analysis determined that students attending school under a YRS calendar outperformed those students attending school under a traditional calendar in terms of achievement and attendance. However, students attending school under a traditional calendar were suspended from school less often than those on a year round calendar. A cohort comparison for individual students who attended school under the YRS approach in both third and fifth grades indicated statistically significant growth in reading, but not in math. A Pearson product correlation yielded statistically significant positive relationships among math and reading performances in both grades. However, achievement was negatively correlated to attendance.

References.QuickCitation: Costa Judith Susan (1987) Comparative Outcomes Of The Clark County School District Year-Round And Nine-Month Schools (Nevada). , University of Nevada, Las Vegas.
References.Title: Comparative Outcomes Of The Clark County School District Year-Round And Nine-Month Schools (Nevada)
References.Abstract: This study compared achievement in reading, mathematics, and language of elementary students attending traditional-calendar nine-month schools with the achievement of elementary students on the 45-15 staggered plan in year-round schools. Also investigated were attendance and enrollment data for elementary students in both types of schools, and teacher evaluation of their respective schools for both types of schools. To investigate achievement effects, an ex post facto criterion-group design was used. The two criterion groups were the two school types--year-round and nine month; the dependent variables were mean school achievement test scores in reading and mathematics (on district-developed criterion-referenced tests at grades two through six and commercially produced norm-referenced tests at grades three and six), and language (on norm-referenced tests at grades three and six). For the analysis of attendance, the average annual percent attendance was calculated for both types of schools by dividing average daily attendance by average daily membership. Further analysis of year-round school attendance was conducted by adjusting this ratio to take into account reduced summer enrollment. Teacher attitudes about their school were compared via their respective mean rating of five Elements of Quality which described school environment or climate. The school sample consisted of seventy-five elementary schools, sixth-grade centers, and middle schools in the Clark County School District in Las Vegas, Nevada. An analysis of covariance using student socioeconomic status, percent minority students, and student "school ability" as the covariates, school structure as the independent variable, and mean school test scores in reading, mathematics, and language as the dependent variables was conducted. No consistent statistically significant differences were found in favor of either type of school, although a statistically significant difference in favor of the nine-month schools was found in six out of ten comparisons at grade three. Attendance at year-round schools was found to be only slightly lower than that at nine-month schools before adjustment was made for the effects of reduced summer enrollment. However, adjustment for this phenomenon showed substantially reduced summer attendance at year-round schools. Teacher opinionnaire data showed no difference in favor of either type of program. (Abstract shortened with permission of author.)

References.QuickCitation: DeCicca Philip (2007) Does full-day kindergarten matter? Evidence from the first two years of schooling. Economics of Education Review 26(1), 67-82
References.Title: Does full-day kindergarten matter? Evidence from the first two years of schooling
References.Abstract: Over the past three decades, enrollment in full-day kindergarten has grown considerably--from roughly one-tenth to just over half of US kindergartners today. Full-day kindergarten reappeared first in the 1960s as an intervention designed to help disadvantaged children ''catch up'' to their peers through additional schooling. More recently, it has gained popularity among non-poor parents and schools, so that children presently enrolled in full-day programs are, on average, very similar to their half-day counterparts in baseline test scores as well as other child, parent and school characteristics. Using longitudinal data, I estimate the impact of full-day kindergarten on standardized test scores in mathematics and reading, as children progress from kindergarten to first grade. I find that full-day kindergarten has sizeable impacts on academic achievement, but the estimated gains are short-lived, particularly for minority children. Given the additional expense of full-day kindergarten, information regarding the size and duration of gains should be of great interest to policy makers.

References.QuickCitation: DeLaro Frank Paul (1994) An analysis of student achievement in year-round and traditional calendar elementary schools. , University of Houston.
References.Title: An analysis of student achievement in year-round and traditional calendar elementary schools
References.Abstract: This study was designed to examine student achievement data of students attending year-round and traditional calendar schools. The focus was on student performance on the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills (TAAS) for the 1991-92 and 1992-93 school years. Comparisons were made between ethnic groups and economically disadvantaged students attending schools that operate on traditional and year-round calendars. Comparisons of third grade student performance on all tests taken were conducted to determine if differences in achievement were statistically significant. The number of districts submitting year-round calendars to the Texas Education Agency has grown steadily since 1991. The concept is rapidly gaining acceptance in Texas, generally for fiscal reasons. Fifty-eight school districts submitted year round calendars in the fall of 1993. Today, minimal Texas data exist regarding the impact on student achievement when implementing year-round schools. Decisions by boards of trustees and administrators to implement new programs, such as year-round schools, should not be based solely on fiscal issues. There is a moral and ethical obligation to determine that new programs do not have a negative impact on student achievement. A best case scenario provides school districts the opportunity to positively impact student achievement while maintaining sound fiscal practices and solvency. Year-round schooling is apparently here to stay in Texas. Should that be the case, it is important that educators and parents have sufficient data for decision making. This study provides additional insight into issues related to the impact of the year-round calendar on student achievement.

References.QuickCitation: Dorsett Richard, Rienzo Cinzia, Niesr Heather Rolfe, Burns Helen, Robertson Barbara-Anne, Thorpe Benjamin, and Wall Kate (2014) Mind the Gap: Evaluation report and executive summary. London: ,
References.Title: Mind the Gap: Evaluation report and executive summary
References.Abstract: Mind the Gap sought to improve the metacognition and academic attainment of pupils in Year 4. There were two aspects to the intervention. The first involved training teachers in how to embed metacognitive approaches in their work, and how to continue to effectively and strategically involve parents. This training took place over a day and was provided by a consultant. The second component focused on parental engagement and offered families the opportunity to participate in a series of facilitated workshops where children and parents work together to create an animated film. Sessions were coordinated by a practitioner who helped participants to think about how they are learning, create learning goals and reflect on their progress; to be metacognitive about the learning process they were engaged in together. The families were offered 2 hours of workshops per week for 5 weeks (10 hours in total). The project targeted schools in four areas of England: Birmingham, Devon, London and Manchester. It was delivered by the Campaign for Learning, with assessments carried out by Durham University. Delivery started in September 2012 and finished in October 2013. The project was evaluated using a randomised controlled trial, which compared the interventions to a ‘business-as-usual’ control group. It is important to note that it was eligibility for the animation course, not participation, that was randomised, so the results must be regarded as estimating the effect of being offered the animation course (alone or in combination with teacher training, as appropriate) rather than participating in it.

[¬s]"The five sessions were carefully designed to encompass elements such as story planning, modelling, trialling the equipment, exploring different animation techniques, filming, and editing. References.QuickCitation: Dunn Eddie Ray (1996) The effect of calendar configuration on elementary students' achievement gains. , Baylor University.
References.Title: The effect of calendar configuration on elementary students' achievement gains
References.Abstract: The purpose of this research was to study the effect of calendar configuration on elementary students' achievement gains in math and reading. The participants in this study were students matched from Traditional calendar and Year-Round (YRE) calendar programs. The Texas Assessment of Academic Skills (TAAS) examination was used to measure student achievement in math and reading because it is the legislatively mandated standardized assessment for public school students in Texas. To accomplish this purpose, a total of 199 Year-Round calendar students from three public school districts in Texas were matched to Traditional calendar students within their respective district. Students were matched according to gender, ethnicity, socioeconomic status, and ability level. They were matched on scaled scores of the reading and math portions of TAAS for the baseline year of 1992-93. Three consecutive years' data were analyzed to measure the degree of gain demonstrated in math and reading. This three-year quasi-experimental study utilized a Randomized Block Design in a 2 (calendar configuration) x 3 (year) repeated measure format. The repeated measure was the year the TAAS subtests of math and reading were taken: Fall 1992, Spring 1994, and Spring 1995. Findings in this study were mixed. Traditional calendar students demonstrated greater achievement gains than their Year-Round calendar counterparts in TAAS math. YRE calendar students demonstrated greater achievement gains in TAAS reading than their Traditional calendar counterparts. Hispanic YRE students realized two consecutive years of gain in reading. Calendar configuration appeared to have no effect upon male students. Female students in YRE programs demonstrated greater gains in TAAS reading for Years Two and Three of the study. Future research concerning the effect of calendar configuration on student achievement gain is recommended which utilizes a research design similar to this study. This should include (1) cohort analysis, (2) longitudinal data, (3) control for variables of interest (race, gender, socioeconomic status, intersession, and calendar type), and (4) the use of the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills examination as the measurement tool.

References.QuickCitation: Dynarski Mark, James-Burdumy Susanne, Moore Mary, Rosenberg Linda, Deke John, and Mansfield Wendy (2004) When Schools Stay Open Late: The National Evaluation of the 21st Century Community Learning Centers Program--New Findings. Washington, D.C.: US Department of Education, National Center for Education Evaluation and Regional Assistance.,
References.Title: When Schools Stay Open Late: The National Evaluation of the 21st Century Community Learning Centers Program--New Findings
References.Publisher: US Department of Education, National Center for Education Evaluation and Regional Assistance.
References.Abstract: After-school programs have grown rapidly in recent years, spurred by rising employment rates of mothers, pressure to increase academic achievement, and concerns about risks to children who are unsupervised during after-school hours. The percentage of public schools offering "extended day" programs (which include before- and after-school programs) more than tripled from 1987 to 1999, from about 13 percent to 47 percent. The federal government's investment in after-school programs has grown rapidly as well. Funding for the 21st Century Community Learning Centers program, created in 1994, rose from $40 million in 1998 to $1 billion in 2002. The program now provides funding to 2,250 school districts to support school-based programs in 7,000 public schools. Some studies of after-school programs have found that these programs increase academic achievement and student safety, as well as reduce negative behaviors such as drug and alcohol use. However, other studies have found that after-school programs have no effect on--and even worsen--certain outcomes, leading to debate over whether the evidence supports increased investment in after-school programs. Four appendixes include response rates and data quality, study design and methods for estimating impacts, sensitivity tests and results for alternative specifications, and subgroup tables

Page 20:
[¬s]"A Typical Elementary School Center The center is open five days a week for three hours a day, serving students in kindergarten through grade six. About 120 students a day come to the center. The first 75 minutes is snack time followed by homework. Certified teachers and aides supervise the homework sessions. The next two sessions are 40 minutes each and include academic and enrichment activities. For the first session, students alternately work on computers to enhance their reading or math skills or meet with a certified teacher for lessons that complement what students worked on with computers. For the next session, students are grouped with other students in their grade and rotate through enrichment activities such as arts and crafts, karate, and fitness and dance. A mix of teachers, instructional aides, and outside organizations lead the enrichment activities. On Fridays, students have free choice for one 40-minute block and use the time to play board games or basketball.[¬e]"

Page 22:
[¬s]"A Typical 21st Century Middle School Center About 45 students participate on an average day. After the school day ends at 1:30 p.m., students gather in the school cafeteria to get a snack followed by homework. After homework time ends, students choose from a variety of activities, such as free time in the gym, board games, table tennis, computer lab, and arts and crafts. A mix of certified teachers and paraprofessionals supervise the homework session and other activities.[¬e]"

References.QuickCitation: Elsberry James Stanton (1992) An evaluation of the implementation of year-round education. , The University of Texas at Austin.
References.Title: An evaluation of the implementation of year-round education
References.Institution: The University of Texas at Austin
References.Abstract: This study evaluated the implementation of a year-round education program in a population that included elementary students in grades preK-6. Data were gathered from student, teacher and parent sources to answer questions about the relationship between the year-round calendar and student achievement and attendance, parent perceptions of family activity planning and instructional effectiveness, teacher personal and professional scheduling, and teacher perceptions of instructional effectiveness. The Texas Assessment of Academic Skills (TAAS) test was used to evaluate student achievement. Scale scores were analyzed for third and fifth-grade students in writing, reading and mathematics. Questionnaires were developed to collect data from parents and teachers for analysis by calendar configuration. An analysis was also conducted that matched parent survey data with student achievement data. Significant increases in student achievement were found for year-round students in the areas of third-grade writing and fifth-grade writing, reading, and mathematics. Year-round students had significantly better attendance patterns than did traditional calendar students. Parents of year-round students perceived the quality of instruction to be better than did parents of traditional calendar children. They also indicated that the year-round calendar was more effective in the overall education of their children. Year-round parents also believed scheduling of family activities was facilitated by the change in calendar. No difference was found for teacher scheduling of personal and professional activities between calendars. Teachers perceived the year-round calendar to be more instructionally effective for students than the traditional calendar. The combination of parent and student achievement data files produced several additional findings. Students of parents who indicated they were more satisfied with school had higher achievement scores than did students of parents who indicated they were less satisfied. Students with high mobility rates had higher achievement on the year-round calendar than did students on the traditional calendar. Student achievement was higher for both English and Spanish speaking students on the year-round calendar.

References.QuickCitation: Espinosa David (2000) A comparison of Iowa Test of Basic Skills scores of students in year -round schools versus non -year -round schools. , University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.
References.Title: A comparison of Iowa Test of Basic Skills scores of students in year -round schools versus non -year -round schools
References.Abstract: Since the establishment of a uniform school calendar of approximately 180 days in the early 20th century, numerous studies have been conducted to investigate the effects of the three-month summer break on the retention of learning by school children. Most studies indicate that long summer vacation results in students forgetting much that was learned during the regular school year. There is an existing controversy about the effectiveness of year-round school calendars. Most of this controversy is generated by studies which do not seem to evidence that this type of calendar results in academic gains. Other studies have shown that students in year-round schools achieve as much or more than students in traditional schools. Some traditional school research studies have investigated the problem of learning loss over long summer breaks, with particular regard to the effect such breaks have on disadvantaged and minority students. The problem of learning loss is well documented. The purpose of this study was to establish a comparison between the traditional, September through June calendar and the year-round calendar with regard to increased student achievement. Given the increasing popularity of the year-round calendar in Chicago, this study was conducted to investigate whether or not increased continuity fostered by the year-round calendar had any kind of impact on the increased academic performance of students. The students in the sample population were continuously exposed to this modality of instruction for a period of three years. The schools under study were paired according to their similarities in geographical location within the City of Chicago, as much as other similarities in social and economic conditions of their students.

Outcomes.OutcomeDescription: The ITBS is a nationally recognized standardized test that was adopted by the Chicago Public Schools as one of the measuring tools to determine student academic achievement. The ITBS is designed and constructed by specialized professional staff at University of Iowa. The test reliability is high, and the interpretation of the results may be assisted by carefully developed norms. The ITBS is categorized and constructed by levels that reflect a consecutive developmental sequence from kindergarten to ninth grade. For its implementation, the different levels are assumed to correspond to the chronological age of the subject students.

References.QuickCitation: Finch Curtis Ellsworth, and Jr (1997) The effect of supplementary computer-assisted instruction upon rural seventh-grade students to improve math scores as measured by the Michigan Educational Assessment Program test. , Walden University.
References.Title: The effect of supplementary computer-assisted instruction upon rural seventh-grade students to improve math scores as measured by the Michigan Educational Assessment Program test
References.Abstract: This quasi-experimental study was designed to explore the effects of short-term, supplementary, computer-assisted instruction (CAI) on improving the math scores of rural, economically-disadvantaged seventh grade students as measured by standardized tests. The study examined the significance of gender, age, time the use of an integrated learning system (ILS), before- and after-school CAI sessions, and the correlation between the math portions of the California Achievement Test (Spring, CAT 16E) and the Michigan Educational Assessment Program (Fall, MEAP) test. All Michigan schools participate in MEAP math testing every school year, five weeks into the school year. Many studies have investigated the effectiveness of CAI upon academic performance for elementary, high school, and university students in urban settings, Past research studies have shown the usefulness of CAI with economically and educationally challenged pupils, as well as low-achieving students, but a limited amount of research has focused upon the math performance of middle level, economically-disadvantaged, rural students. The population of this study consisted of the entire 1996-1997 seventh grade population of 180 students at a northern Michigan middle school. Thirty-five students were randomly chosen for the CAI experimental group from a group of 60 volunteers. The five week, daily, CAI sessions occurred in a before- and after-school format. The control group consisted of 35 students randomly chosen from the remaining students. The spring math CAT 16E (pretest) was used to verify there existed no significant difference in the groups. The impact of CAI upon the MEAP math test (posttest) was examined by 12 hypotheses. No significant difference on the posttest was found between those students who received the compressed CAI instruction and those who did not based on gender, time on the ILS, and the before- and after-school format. A correlation at the.01 level existed between the pretest and posttests. Additional data regarding MEAP reading scores showed a correlation at the.05 level to the MEAP math results.

References.QuickCitation: Gandara Patricia, and Fish Judy (1994) Year-round schooling as an avenue to major structural reform. Educational Evaluation and Policy Analysis 16(1), 67-85
References.Title: Year-round schooling as an avenue to major structural reform
References.Abstract: This article reports on a study that sought to experiment with multiple education reforms in the context of an extended school calendar year. Three schools, with very different characteristics, undertook to extend their school year to approximately 223 days (from the previous 180 days), reorganize funding to provide more days of schooling for many students, and increase the length of the work year, and consequently the salaries, of teachers. All three schools were able to demonstrate increases in academic achievement, a high level of parent and teacher satisfaction, and a cost-effective use of existing school facilities. Implications for education reform and year-round schooling are discussed.

References.QuickCitation: Gentilcore John Curtis (2002) The effect of an after -school academic intervention service on a New York State eighth grade English language arts assessment: A case study. , Hofstra University.
References.Title: The effect of an after -school academic intervention service on a New York State eighth grade English language arts assessment: A case study
References.Abstract: The New York State Board of Regents, responsible for the supervision of educational activities in conjunction with the New York State Education Department, has set higher learning standards for all students. To help students reach standards outlined by the New York State Regents, assessments in English-Language Arts were designed to identify eighth grade students who might not pass English Regents Examinations. Students at risk of failing Regents Examinations are mandated by the New York State Education Department to receive Academic Intervention Services, or AIS. This study investigated the effectiveness of AIS in one school over a period of two years. The purpose of this study was to examine the relationship between participation in an English Language Arts AIS program and eighth grade student performance on the New York State English Language Arts Assessment. Further, this study explored additional relationships by type of program, faculty involvement and biosocial variables including sex, race, and socio-economic status. This is a quasi-experimental, control-treatment, post intervention study of an AIS program over two years in a suburban middle school on Long Island, New York. Participants included in the study were eighth grade students who were enrolled in the middle school in 1999–2000 and 2000–2001. The treatment group is a sample of 114 AIS students included in this study, 93.4% of the AIS population. Overall, this study revealed no significant differences between control and treatment groups. Girls scored higher than boys, but the sample size for other biosocial variables such as race and socio-economic status was too small to provide useful information. Instruction by full versus part time staff yielded no significant results on ELA mean scores. The study underscores the importance of continuing research in the area of Academic Intervention Services in New York State. Suggestions for future research include an emphasis on student learning styles, organizational settings and effective teaching strategies and instructional materials.

References.QuickCitation: Gottfredson Denise, Cross Amanda Brown, Wilson Denise, Rorie Melissa, and Connell Nadine (2010) Effects of participation in after-school programs for middle school students: A randomized trial. Journal of Research on Educational Effectiveness 3(3), 282-313
References.Title: Effects of participation in after-school programs for middle school students: A randomized trial
References.ParentTitle: Journal of Research on Educational Effectiveness
References.Abstract: This study assessed the effects of attending an after-school program (ASP) on a range of outcomes for middle school youths. The program operated for 9 hr per week for 30 weeks and included attendance monitoring and reinforcement, academic assistance, a prevention curriculum, and recreational programming. Participants were 447 students randomly assigned either to the ASP or to after-school activities as usual. Program attendance was sporadic. Although treatment students experienced increased exposure to ASPs relative to controls, nearly all youth in both groups reported participating in some organized activity during the after-school hours, and the number of different activities in which youths reported being involved did not differ across groups. Participation in the treatment reduced time spent with friends with no adults present during the after-school hours. No differences between treatment and control youths were found on measures of conduct problems, academic performance, school attendance, or any of the intermediate behaviors and attitudes targeted. The study replicates findings from the national evaluation of the 21st Century Community Learning Centers Program for middle school students using a more rigorous research design. (Contains 1 figure, 6 tables, and 7 footnotes.)
References.Authors: Gottfredson Denise ; Cross Amanda Brown; Wilson Denise ; Rorie Melissa ; Connell Nadine ;

References.QuickCitation: Grolnick Wendy S, Farkas Melanie S, Sohmer Richard, Michaels Sarah, and Valsiner Jaan (2007) Facilitating motivation in young adolescents: Effects of an after-school program. Journal of applied developmental psychology 28(4), 332-344
References.Title: Facilitating motivation in young adolescents: Effects of an after-school program
References.Abstract: This study examined the effects of a motivationally facilitative after-school program on 7th grade students' autonomous motivation, learning goals, school engagement, and performance in science class. Pairs of students were individually matched on sex, race/ethnicity, free lunch status, and science grades and each member was randomly assigned to either a 15 week, after-school program or a control group. Students (N = 90) completed questionnaires regarding their motivation, and engagement before and after the program. Science, math, social studies, and English teachers rated students' levels of classroom engagement. Students participating in the Investigators' Club increased in learning goals, engagement in school and in science class, and science grades, and decreased in performance goals relative to the controls. Effects of the program as well as drop-out and completer information, are discussed in terms of the goal of facilitating motivation in disadvantaged middle school students.© 2007 Elsevier Inc. [¬s]"The Investigators' Club was developed as a manual-based set of curricular units — each with a particular content focused on science (e.g., air pressure, sinking and floating, mass and motion) that did not overlap with that of the science class curriculum, and with a set of common activities. Each unit involved a discrepant event, e.g., “what will happen when I drop this can full of water with a small hole punched in its side from the very top of this ladder?” Then, during “Circle Up Time” students in the full group predict what will happen when the experiment is run and provide an argument for their position. In these “position driven” discussions the teacher helps students clarify and explicate their positions. The leader does not evaluate children's thinking per se, but rather encourages them to build on each other's ideas and theories. In these discussions, students become facile at evidence based reasoning and in taking responsibility for their own positions with support from the group leader. “Circle Up Time” is followed by small group collaboration, in which students work with materials to address some issue pertaining to the topic at hand. The students then meet back in a circle to present results and explanations to the larger group. At the end of the session, students carry through and then discuss the experiment.[¬e]"

References.QuickCitation: Haenn Joseph F (1996) Evaluating the Promise of Single-Track Year-Round Schools. New York: American Educational Research Association, 1-19
References.Title: Evaluating the Promise of Single-Track Year-Round Schools
References.Abstract: Results from the first year of implementation of year-round schools in a school district that educates students from a medium-sized city and the surrounding county are presented to add to the body of knowledge about year-round schools. Two single-track, year-round elementary schools (kindergarten through grade 5) were established in Durham (North Carolina). One school adopted a core knowledge curriculum, while the other chose a more traditional approach. Both were attendance zone schools, rather than magnet schools, but in both cases a majority of parents had to approve the year-round concept and parents were allowed to send their children to other schools. Evaluation data supported the conclusion that the year-round schools had a significant positive effect on the achievement of students. There was also reason to believe that instructional planning at the school level was improved by the need to coordinate assessment and remediation services. Although disadvantaged students did not participate in the enrichment programs and the remediation programs between the sessions to the extent planners had hoped, those students who did receive the inter-session remediation were better prepared to resume their educations after breaks. The schools can be considered an important addition to the learning opportunities in the Durham schools. (Contains eight tables and six references.) (SLD)

References.QuickCitation: Hasselmeier Julia Elizabeth (1997) Traditional vs. year-round education on academic achievement. , University of Houston-Clear Lake.
References.Title: Traditional vs. year-round education on academic achievement
References.Abstract: The purpose of this research was to evaluate the effectiveness of traditional vs. year-round education on academic achievement. Literature was reviewed to note previous experience with traditional and year-round schools. This study looked at T.A.A.S. (Texas Assessment of Academic Skills) test results from students in traditional and year-round schools from the Deer Park Independent School District and the Pasadena Independent School District. Tables were used to report the group comparisons and the mean scores for the traditional and the year-round students. Percentile rank scores were also reported for each group. There was no significant difference between math and reading scores among the third grade group. There was a significant difference (p $<$.001) on both math and reading achievement favoring year-round students at the fourth grade level. At the fifth grade level there was a significant difference, (p $<$.001), again favoring year-round students on both math and reading achievement.

References.QuickCitation: Hausner Mary E. Interrante (2000) The Impact of Kindergarten Intervention Project Accelerated Literacy on Emerging Literacy Concepts and Second Grade Reading Comprehension. : ERIC,
References.Title: The Impact of Kindergarten Intervention Project Accelerated Literacy on Emerging Literacy Concepts and Second Grade Reading Comprehension
References.Abstract: This study investigated the relationship between success of an early intervention program Project Accelerated Literacy in the kindergarten year and success in second grade reading performance. The intervention was given only to students who demonstrated a literacy delay on kindergarten literacy assessments. Subjects were 283 kindergarten students enrolled in 6 at-risk schools in a large urban school district. The experimental group participated in the Project Accelerated Literacy program, an extended day intervention in addition to the half-day kindergarten session; the control group participated only in the kindergarten half-day. All students were tested at the beginning and conclusion of the 30-week intervention using subtests of the Observation Survey. A statistically significant difference between control and experimental groups was found prior to the intervention. After 30 weeks of intervention, the difference between the two groups was no longer statistically significant except in Writing Vocabulary. The experimental group scored higher than the control group in Writing Vocabulary after the intervention. Two years later, the students were tested for reading comprehension and cognitive ability using the Iowa Test of Basic Skills and the Cognitive Ability Test. The control group scored significantly higher than the experimental group; the difference decreased when scores were adjusted for cognitive ability. Findings suggest that a kindergarten literacy intervention can significantly increase the literacy scores of low performing students, and that at-risk students need more than one literacy intervention to retain the gains made in their kindergarten year.

Outcomes.Title: Letter Identification (t-test)
Outcomes.OutcomeDescription: Post-test T-test results for letter identification extracted for ES calculation. Letter Identification (LID) has a possible score of 54. Students are given a point for each randomly listed alphabet letter both upper and lower case including different types of print for "a" and "g".

Outcomes.Title: Writing Vocabulorty (t-test)
Outcomes.OutcomeDescription: Writing Vocabulary (WV) is a timed assessment. The student has ten minutes to write as many words as possible, starting with his/her name. Score is unlimited; one point for each correctly spelled word.

Outcomes.Title: Concepts about print (T-test)
Outcomes.OutcomeDescription: Concepts About Print (CAP) is a test of book handling, directionality and print concepts. There is a possible score of 24 points. Students are given a point for each concept they can point to or identify. There is no reading required.

Outcomes.Title: Hearing sounds in words (t-test)
Outcomes.OutcomeDescription: Hearing Sounds In Words (HSIW) The student is asked to listen to a dictated sentence and write as many letters and words that represent that sentence. There is a possible score of 37; the student is given a point for each correct letter representing a sound in the dictation.

References.QuickCitation: Heaberlin Robert Lee, and Jr (2000) The effects of year -round education on elementary school students. , University of Georgia.
References.Title: The effects of year -round education on elementary school students
References.Abstract: This research study was designed to investigate the impact of Year-Round Education (YRE) on students at Newnan Crossing Elementary School based on the variables of student achievement, student discipline, and student attendance. This was accomplished with two sets of comparisons-first, comparing matched students at Newnan Crossing Elementary School during the 1996–97 school year (final year of a traditional calendar approach) and the 1997–98 school year (the first full year of a YRE approach), and second, comparing Newnan Crossing Elementary School with a similar traditional calendar elementary school in the same district during the 1997–98 school year. Student achievement was measured by the Total Reading and Total Math scores on the Iowa Test of Basic Skills (ITBS). Student discipline was measured by the number of out-of-school suspensions and discipline cases referred to the Coweta County Superintendent's Office. Student attendance was based on the number of days a student was absent during the school year. A paired-samples t-test was used to determine the statistical significance of the mean values for each dependent variable in a comparison of matched students at Newnan Crossing Elementary School. An independent samples t-test was used to determine the statistical significance of the mean values for each dependent variable in a comparison of Newnan Crossing and the similar traditional calendar elementary school. The results of this study indicated that the YRE approach may be considered as an equally effective approach as the traditional calendar approach in the areas of student achievement, student discipline, and student attendance.

References.QuickCitation: Hirsch Barton J, Hedges Larry V, Stawicki JulieAnn, and Mekinda Megan A (2011) After-school programs for high school students: An evaluation of After School Matters. : ,
References.Title: After-school programs for high school students: An evaluation of After School Matters
References.Abstract: After-school programs have attracted a strong and growing constituency among both academic theorists and policy makers. Yet participation in after-school programs is extremely sparse at the high school level. Clearly there is a need to develop more attractive after-school programs for HS youth, which makes After School Matters (ASM), one of the country’s largest programs for this group, an important program to study. After School Matters offers paid apprenticeship-type experiences in a wide array of areas, such as technology, arts, and sports. Each apprenticeship involves work in the designated area, learning and making use of relevant skills to accomplish a task. Instructors are present to provide information, guidance, and feedback, and to introduce students to the standards, language, and culture of that line of work. The experience presumably also helps students begin to appreciate and adapt to the culture of the workplace and improve the “soft skills” increasingly demanded by employers. The instructors have expertise in – and in many instances earn their livelihood through – the activity that is the focus of the apprenticeship. Most instructors are notteachers. Apprentices were paid a stipend equivalent to $5/hour during our study.

References.QuickCitation: Hobbs Connie L (2012) Effects of an afterschool program on elementary and middle school math achievement in Georgia schools. , Liberty University.
References.Title: Effects of an afterschool program on elementary and middle school math achievement in Georgia schools
References.Abstract: Due to the demands placed on schools to make Adequate Yearly Progress (AYP) on state standardized tests, many districts are looking at afterschool programs to help bridge the gap in achievement for students who are at-risk for failing to master standards. The purpose of this study was to analyze the effect an afterschool program had on upper-elementary and middle school at-risk student's math achievement on state standardized tests. The study scrutinized an afterschool program in north Georgia that is providing a 21st Century Community Learning Center (21st CCLC) for students Kindergarten through 8th grade. Standardized test scores in mathematics on the Georgia Criterion Referenced Competency Test (CRCT) between at-risk upper-elementary and middle school students who participated in the afterschool program were compared to a similar group of students who did not participate in the program. The researcher investigated quantitatively whether participation in the afterschool program had an impact on student achievement in mathematics. For this sample of 180 at-risk students, the ANCOVA method of data analysis was utilized to determine if there were differences between the groups of students in the afterschool program and those not in the program, based on 2011 CRCT math scores. This research study found no significant differences in math CRCT scores of those who attended the afterschool program and those similar students not attending the afterschool program.
References.Comments: CODERS: Treat as single study. Use totals for CRCT maths 2011 in Table 4.1 for post-test only comparison as primary outcome (this will underestimate the effect, but gain score SDs not available). Report Elementary and Middle school results separately as secondary outcomes (post-test only)

References.QuickCitation: Johnson Nancy P (1984) The Effects Of Year-Round School Programs On Pupil Achievement In Selected Schools In The Los Angeles Unified School District. , Pepperdine University.
References.Title: The Effects Of Year-Round School Programs On Pupil Achievement In Selected Schools In The Los Angeles Unified School District
References.Abstract: Research Objectives. This study was undertaken to ascertain whether fifth grade pupils who had participated in year-round school programs will show higher reading and mathematics scores than a similar group of fifth graders who participated only in traditional school programs. Procedure. Twelve year-round and twelve traditional schools from the Los Angeles Unified School District were selected to participate in this casual-comparative (ex post facto) study. The year-round schools selected were those that had been in year-round programs since 1980 and, at the same time could be "matched" with traditional schools. Some of the variables considered in "matching" the schools were: socio/economic level of the school location, racial/ethnic composition of the school's pupil population, special programs offered to pupils, school size, and type of community surrounding the school. The 1,041 pupils in the study were selected from fifth grade populations of the twenty-four schools. The pupils ranged in age from ten through twelve years. Pupil selection was based on the following criteria: (1) they were in the school in 1979-80 as third graders and continued in the school through the 1981-82 school year as fifth graders; (2) they were fluent in speaking English; and (3) they had complete CTBS scores in reading and mathematics for both 1979-80 and 1981-82 school years. The data on the pupils were collected at school sites and from the Research and Evaluation Branch of the Los Angeles Unified School District. Subprogram ANOVA and subprogram PEARSON CORR of the Statistical Package for the Social Sciences, SPSS system, were used to perform statistical analysis of the data in order to determine statistical significance of the eight null hypotheses of the study. Findings. The following are findings of the study: (1) There was a significant interaction effect on reading between calendar and sex. Year-round school girls scored significantly lower than year-round school boys, and lower than traditional school boys and girls. (2) There was a significant main effect of calendar on mathematics. Pupils in the traditional schools scored significantly higher than pupils in the year-round schools. (3) The relationship between absence and achievement in both reading and mathematics, though low, was significant in most cases and always negative.

References.QuickCitation: Kauh Tina J (2011) AfterZone: Outcomes for youth participating in Providence’s citywide after-school system. : , 1-109
References.Title: AfterZone: Outcomes for youth participating in Providence’s citywide after-school system
References.Abstract: This report presents findings from a two-year quasi-experimental evaluation of the "AfterZone"--a citywide system-building effort in Providence, Rhode Island, that aims to provide high-quality, accessible out-of-school-time services to middle school youth. The AfterZone model is unique in that it is built on a network of "neighborhood campuses" anchored by one or two middle schools; this structure provides youth the opportunity to participate in sports, arts and skills-enhancing programs in both community- and school-based settings. The report summarizes the patterns of youth participation in the AfterZone during the two-year period (in terms of amount, breadth and engagement); examines the benefits youth experience from participating after one and two school years; and presents implications for funders, policymakers and program leaders interested in implementing their own citywide out-of-school-time system. Appended are: (1) Measures; (2) Attrition; (3) Analyses; (4) Effect Sizes; (5) Accounting for Baseline Group Differences; (6) Subgroup Analyses; (7) Two-Year AfterZone Participants; (8) Participation Analyses; and (9) Correlations Among Dimensions of Participation. (Contains 33 tables, 9 figures and 85 footnotes.) [For the "AfterZone: Outcomes for Youth Participating in Providence's Citywide After-School System. Executive Summary", see ED522989.]

[¬s]"it employs a single set of stan- dards to encourage high-quality programming and provides training and support to programs and providers within its system. Second, it is structured around a neighborhood “campus” model, where services are offered at multiple sites in a geographi- cally clustered area, known as a “zone.” Zones encompass several programs located in community- based facilities, such as libraries and recreational and art centers, with safe transportation to and from the facilities coordinated by PASA. However, each zone is anchored by one or two middle schools, where the program day begins and ends for every youth. Third, the AfterZone’s structure and orga- nizational practices are rooted in the goal of being developmentally appropriate for middle-school-age youth. For instance, at the beginning of each pro- gram session, youth are offered an extensive menu of program options. This both gives them a sense of agency by allowing them to choose how they spend their time and aims to expose them to new[¬e]"

Page 19:

In addition, the campus structure of the AfterZone enables youth to safely travel away from school grounds, which further provides a sense of inde- pendence and introduces youth to new environ- ments and community resources. Fourth, PASA not only coordinates the key players in the AfterZone system but also leads the check-in and check-out process each day at the zones it leads, provides its own academically oriented enrichment activities to AfterZone youth through “Club AfterZone” and employs AfterZone staff to supervise and coordinate these activities.[¬e]"

References.Abstract: The traditional organization of American schools may no longer be adequate for meeting present and future needs in public education. One of the major responses to these needs has been the consideration of a change in the school calendar from the traditional nine month calendar to a year round calendar in order to provide education to the ever increasing student population and as a strategy for improving the achievement of students that are considered at-risk. Using an ex-post facto, posttest control group design with matching, this study investigates the impact of the year round calendar on achievement, and the degree to which it differentially affects at-risk students. In addition, the study examines achievement impact in relation to the SES level of the school and the length of implementation of the YRE program . Fourth, fifth, and sixth grade traditional calendar and year round students were matched on their standard reading and math subtest percentile scores of the 1992 Norm-referenced Assessment Program for Texas (NAPT). T-tests for related samples were calculated using the Bonferroni method on mean achievement scores of the 1993 NAPT to determine if there was a statistically significant difference between the two groups. Results of the data analyses indicated statistically significant differences in math and reading achievement for all students, and especially in reading for at-risk students. Statistical significance in favor of YRE was also found in both reading and math for low SES schools. Differences in achievement with respect to number of years of individual school implementation of YRE yielded results of statistical significance in five out of six comparisons. In order to determine practical significance effect size was calculated. The year round school structure yielded practically significant results in 23 out o f 26 data analysis comparisons, with effect sizes ranging from .21 to .88. In summary, the results from this study reveal that mean scores and effect sizes favored the year round calendar in all comparisons. However, the magnitude of the differences varied somewhat across analyses

References.QuickCitation: Kuner-Roth Bonni (1985) A Comparison Of Academic Achievement Of Students In A Year Round School District With A Conventional School Year District (Forty-Five-Fifteen Plan, Attendance, Illinois). , Temple University.
References.Title: A Comparison Of Academic Achievement Of Students In A Year Round School District With A Conventional School Year District (Forty-Five-Fifteen Plan, Attendance, Illinois)
References.Abstract: The purpose of this study was to investigate the extent to which differences existed in students academic performance while attending school on a year round school plan (45-15 plan) as compared with academic performance of students while attending school on a traditional school year plan. Specifically, the study determined if there was a difference in teacher grades and achievement test scores of students in the subjects of language arts, mathematics, and reading as well as the number of days of student absence between the school districts and within each school district by gender. The population was from two school districts located in suburban areas of Chicago, Illinois. Each group was composed of 90 male and 90 female students randomly selected from students who attended school in the same district from third grade through seventh grade in regular education classes to form a total sample of 360 students. An experimental design, the pretest-posttest control group design, was chosen because equivalent groups were achieved by randomization with the measure of significant differences tested in 7th grade using 3rd grade as the covariates. A two-way analysis of covariance (ANCOVA) was computed for each hypothesis to determine whether there was a significant difference between groups and within group by gender. The findings indicated that year round school students probably earned higher teacher grades in language arts than traditional school year students. By contrast, traditional school year students probably scored higher on language arts and reading achievement tests. Only in reading achievement scores was there a significant difference in the interaction of school and gender. Within the traditional school year group females scored higher than males, but within the year round school group females scored lower than males. There was no significant difference between groups for teacher grades and achievement test scores in mathematics. One finding was repeated for each hypothesis, there was no significant difference within each school district group by gender. Mixed findings have resulted from this study, therefore this researcher was unable to conclude that an advantage has been demonstrated for either type of school district based on teacher grades and achievement test scores.

Outcomes.Title: Iowa Tests of Basic Skills (ITBS) Reading
Outcomes.OutcomeDescription: The traditional year school district chose the Iowa Tests of Basic Skills for testing in both grades three and seven. Harris (Buros, 1978) analyzed the Iowa Tests of Basic Skills as a test battery designed to provide information on the status of pupil development in the basic skill areas. The Levels Edition included tests in the five major skill areas of reading comprehension, language arts, mathematics, vocabulary, and w ork-study skills.

References.QuickCitation: Langberg Joshua M, Smith Bradley H, Bogle Kristin E, Schmidt Jonathan D, Cole Wesley R, and Pender Carolyn A. S (2007) A pilot evaluation of small group challenging horizons program (CHP) a randomized trial. Journal of Applied School Psychology 23(1), 31-58
References.Title: A pilot evaluation of small group challenging horizons program (CHP) a randomized trial
References.Abstract: This study examined the efficacy of an after-school program, the Challenging Horizons Program (CHP), that met four days a week and focused on improving organization, academic skills, and classroom behavior. The CHP was compared with a community control that included involvement in a district-run after-school program that met one to three days a week and focused on preparation for standardized testing. Participants were 48 middle-school youth, referred as experiencing a combination of learning and behavior problems, randomly assigned to either the CHP or the control. Parent and teacher ratings of behavioral and academic functioning were collected at the beginning of the academic year and again after one semester of intervention. Relative to the control, participants in the CHP made significant improvements in parent rated academic progress, self-esteem, and overall severity of problem. While teacher ratings did not reach significance, CHP participants made medium effect size improvements in academic progress and small improvements in overall severity. Core class grades and discipline records were also examined to provide a broad picture of functioning beyond rating scale data.
