References.QuickCitation: Zimmer Ron, Hamilton Laura, and Christina Rachel (2010) After-school tutoring in the context of no child left behind: Effectiveness of two programs in the Pittsburgh public schools. Economics of Education Review 29(1), 18-28
References.Title: After-school tutoring in the context of no child left behind: Effectiveness of two programs in the Pittsburgh public schools
References.Abstract: The No Child Left Behind (NCLB) legislation has created pressure for districts to improve their students’ proficiency levels on state tests. Districts that fail to meet their academic targets for 3 years must use their Title I funds to pay for supplemental education services (SES) that provide tutoring or other academic instruction. Many districts, including the Pittsburgh Public Schools (PPS), have also adopted additional tutoring programs designed to help students reach proficiency goals. This paper examines student participation and achievement in two PPS tutoring programs—the NCLB-mandated SES program and a state-developed tutoring program. We examine the characteristics of students participating in each program, the effects of participation on student achievement, and the program features that are associated with improved achievement.

dent achievement trajectories before, during, and after the
students participated in these programs. Therefore, our
analysis used data from the 2000–2001 to the 2005–2006

"In the period under examination, students in Pittsburgh
took three kinds of annual achievement tests in reading
and math,4 varying with the school year and grade. In con-
sequence, we had no consistent scale on which to gauge
absolute changes in student achievement over time. We
therefore converted all scaled test score results into rank-
based z-scores, by year and grade, with a mean of zero and
a standard deviation of one. Speciﬁcally, we sort all stu-
dent scores by rank then convert them to z-scores normed
across the entire district-wide population of tested stu-
dents in that subject and grade. This conversion does not
require that students have the same rank on one test as
on another, as random differences in student ranks across
different tests would introduce noise, but not bias, to the
analysis."
"The conversion of scaled scores to rank-based
z-scoresmeansthatwecannotmake claims about the abso-
lute amount of learning in one school or another (lacking a
psychometrically valid developmental scale), but it permits
an examination ofchanges in rank with fewer assumptions
thanwould be needed under other kinds ofscaling. For fur-
ther discussion ofthe use ofrank-based z-scores, see Gill et
al. (2005) and Kirby et al. (2002).[¬e]"

Page 6:
[¬s]"Ultimately, we are interested in the effect student par-
ticipation in the SES and EAP programs have on student
achievement. To estimate these effects, the counterfactual
must be estimated. In other words, we must explore how
students exposed to these programswould have performed
in the absence of those options."
"Therefore, we used a quasi-experimental design known as
a ﬁxed-effect model as our primary means of estimating
the effect. Researchers often use ﬁxed effects as a means of
reducing selection bias[¬e]"

[¬s]"Districts that fail to meet their academic targets for 3 years must use their Title I funds to pay for supplemental education services (SES) that provide tutoring or other academic instruction. Many districts, including the Pittsburgh Public Schools (PPS), have also adopted additional tutoring programs designed to help students reach proﬁciency goals. This paper examines student participation and achievement in two PPS tutoring programs—the NCLB-mandated SES program and a state- developed tutoring program. We examine the characteristics of students participating in each program, the effects of participation on student achievement, and the program features that are associated with improved achievement.[¬e]"

Page 2:
[¬s]"Districts are required by federal law to use a portion of Title I funding to provide SES as an option for low-income students (as generally deﬁned by eli- gibility for free or reduced-price lunch) attending schools that have failed to meet state goals for “adequate yearly progress” for three consecutive years. 2 In PPS, SES were ﬁrst offered to students in the 2004–2005 school year. These services are free to parents and students, must be provided outside the regular school day (after school or during the summer), and are intended to provide tutoring geared toward raising students’ proﬁ- ciency in mathematics and reading."
"In 2003–2004, Pennsylvania established the educa- tional assistance program (EAP), which provides extended learning opportunities for students by funding evidence- based tutoring 3 for 82 of the state’s most academically challenged school districts. Tutors are hired and man- aged by the districts and the services can be provided before school, after school, weekends, and/or during the summer. PPS’s EAP tutoring sessions occur within the schools the students attend and the tutors are a com- bination of school teachers within the schools, retired teachers, and college students.[¬e]"

Page 5:
[¬s]"Participants for the SES and EAP program are all students who attended the SES or EAP program at least one session, respectively. Participants in both programs are all students who attended the SES and EAP program at least one session each. Students eligible for the SES are low-income students (deﬁned by free-and-reduced lunch status) attending a school in the second year of corrective action through NCLB. Eligibility for EAP is deﬁned as any student attending a district school providing EAP services. To be eligible to participate in both programs, the student has to be a low- income student attending a school in the second year of corrective action through and attending a school offering EAP services. Because virtually all district students are eligible for the EAP program, the students who are counted as eligible for both programs are the same students who are considered eligible for SES.[¬e]"

Outcomes.Title: Reading achievement - extended school time
Outcomes.OutcomeDescription: Robust standard errors  - have been corrected for clustering - outcomes adjusted for clustering but not baseline. In the period under examination, students in Pittsburgh took three kinds of annual achievement tests in reading and math,4 varying with the school year and grade. In con- sequence, we had no consistent scale on which to gauge absolute changes in student achievement over time. We therefore converted all scaled test score results into rank- based z-scores, by year and grade, with a mean of zero and a standard deviation of one. Speciﬁcally, we sort all stu- dent scores by rank then convert them to z-scores normed across the entire district-wide population of tested stu- dents in that subject and grade.
